narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This course was my introduction to Calculus and it taught me how to apply limits.
I learned the foundations about calculus and how the math work structure in Yale looks like.
I learned the why in math and not just the equations. I was challenged to think beyond the math itself and applying the concepts.

I developed a foundational understanding of calculus principles including limits, derivatives, and linear approximation. I also developed the skill of asking for help and communicating my mathematical understanding through words.
newton's method,optimization
Didnt really learn a ton; I remembered most of my stuff from AB Calculus in highschool. However, Newtons Method was new to me and an interesting thing to think about.
I gained a deeper understanding on the base of Calculus.
How to apply math theories and genuinely understand how they work.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I had difficulties keeping up with lessons in class but I was able to study after and understand it better.

I think the psets helped prepare me to better understand the course. However, I feel like the course review was rushed in the end and felt like I didnt have enough time to study, but this may be because we had to balance our english essay at the same time.

Strengths: incredible teachers and teaching intuition; covered material to an appropriate depth; course was structured to provide students of all mathematical backgrounds an intro to calculus

Weaknesses: Canvas modules (the videos could've been updated to provide the watchers with better context before diving into an example solution); needed greater variety of ULA office hours
the course had a lot of support,ULAs,and office hours if students were stuck.

Strengths: Insightful, New approaches to math

Weakness: Fast-paced

Obviously I took it in a 6 week period, but it felt like with Su Jis teaching style the struggling before being taught the material was the entirety of the class and youd only be given a definition or an explanation at the very end. I obviously cant look at the exam grades, but I wonder how that impacted the split between Bobbys grades and Su Jis for the course
The fast pace made it a little hard to process things but I loved how she wanted us to work in groups to understand certain problems.
It was a very good course, but I did not utilize the resources as much as I should have (office hours, ula's, etc.)

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, I would recommend this course specifically to students who have not yet taken any calculus classes in high school.
I would definitely recommend it to students that have no background in calculus and are curious.
Yes for beginners or anyone trying to gain a stronger foundation for calc in the fall
Definitely! Coming in, I thought QR would be my greatest weakness. This class actually had me excited to go learn.
yeah it's a good .5 credit.
Yes! I think its a great intro to calculus, even if I didnt get much out of it
Yes, for someone who hasnt taken calculus this gets you on the right path.
Yes, it gives a really good base for calculus 1.

narratives.question_text: How will you use the knowledge and skills you learned in this course in your future endeavors?
comments: I will apply my knowledge on limits when I take my next math course in the fall.
I will use this for other math classes and majors that I might want to explore in the future.
From this experience I will better be prepared in terms of what to expect for calc at yale, and I know how to do my psets and how much time I must set aside each week
I will use the problem solving skills and calculus skills in my future endeavors.
If I plan on taking another calculus class, this class would be the reason why.

I will not continue calculus, but the knowledge I learned in this class will help me with other QR courses in the sense that I have an idea of how they are structured and what I need out of them to succeed.
